This paper is primarily focused on computer vision (CV) and machine learning (LG) techniques for face aging, which suggests that cs.CV and cs.LG are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also involves the use of prior knowledge and attention mechanisms, which are common in artificial intelligence (AI) research, making cs.AI a likely sub-category as well. Additionally, the paper involves the synthesis of photorealistic images, which falls under multimedia (MM) research. Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of face aging in human-computer interaction (HC), which suggests that cs.HC is also a possible sub-category.
